revision.text:
==English==

===Etymology===
First attested in 1644. Perhaps a {{back-form|en|abomination|nocap=1}}.<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=4}}</ref> Alternatively, perhaps from {{der|en|LL.|abōminātus}}, past participle of {{m|la|abōminarī||to deprecate as an ill omen}}, from {{m|la|ab}} + {{m|la|ominari||to forebode, presage}}, from {{m|la|omen}}.<ref>{{R:MW3 1976|page=5}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/əˈbɒm.əˌneɪt/|/əˈbɒm.ɪˌneɪt/|a=US}}
* {{sense|adjective}} {{IPA|en|/əˈbɒm.əˌneɪt/|/əˈbɒm.ɪˌneɪt/|/əˈbɒm.ə.nət/|a=US}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-abominate.ogg|a=US}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q7979-Soundguys-abominate.wav|a=UK}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# {{lb|en|rare}} {{cap|abominable}}; [[detest]]ed. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=6}}</ref>

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To feel [[disgust]] towards; to [[loathe]] or [[detest]] thoroughly; to [[hate]] in the highest degree, as if with religious [[dread]]. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{syn|en|abhor}}
#* {{quote-book|en|passage="Much as I '''abominate''' writing, I would not give up Mr. Collins's correspondence for any consideration."|title=Pride and Prejudice|author=Jane Austen|year=1813}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|colloquial}} To dislike strongly. {{defdate|First attested in the late 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: I absolutely '''abominate''' waking up early on weekends.

====Synonyms====
